## **Connect Source Control \(Initial Setup\)**

When you click **Connect Source Control** from the **Setup Guides and References** option in the **Overview** section, or select **Sync from GitHub/GitLab** in the top right corner, the **Source Control** panel opens on the right side of your dashboard.

This panel allows you to authenticate and connect your **GitHub** or **GitLab** repository to Docuwiz, enabling automated file synchronization \(see Figure 1\).

![](data:image/png;base64,)

### **Key Elements**

**Tabs**

- **Connect & Import:** Use this tab to link your repository and import files. *\(This tab is selected and highlighted by default when you begin the setup.\)*
- **Commit & Push:** Use this tab later to push updated files back to your repository.

**Select Source Control**

- Choose your preferred platform  **GitHub** or **GitLab**.
- The selected provider is highlighted in **blue**.

**GitHub/GitLab URL Field**

- Enter the full repository URL, including the branch name where your .yaml, .yml, or .json files are stored.
- Example:[** **https://github.com/username/repository\-name/tree/branch\-name](https://github.com/username/repository-name/tree/branch-name)

**Token Field**

- Enter your **personal access token** generated from GitHub or GitLab to enable secure authentication.
- Learn more about ***Prerequisites for Generating a Personal Access Token ***

**Save & Continue Button**

- Click **Save & Continue** to store your repository details and proceed with file synchronization.

>

## **Commit & Push Configuration**

After you connect your repository, Docuwiz automatically opens the **Commit & Push** view.

This screen allows you to sync specific documentation filesor all filesfrom Docuwiz back to your **GitHub** or **GitLab** branch \(see Figure 2\).

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Figure 2: Commit and Push

### **Key Elements**

**Git Details Section**

- Displays your selected platform \(**GitHub** or **GitLab**\) along with the configured repository URL and authentication token.

**Branch Name**

- Shows the branch where your changes will be pushed.
- Docuwiz automatically generates a branch name based on your workspace and timestamp.
- Example: workspace\_docu\-10th\-Oct\-2025\-13\-04

**Commit Message**

- Enter a brief description for your commit.
- Example**:** *Updated API specs and guide files.*

**Select Files Section**

- Displays all **Guides** and **References** available in your workspace.
- You can choose to:
  - **Sync All Files** to push all documentation files, or
  - Select individual files such as *Use Cases \(Guide\)* or[ ](http://bump.sh)[*Bump.sh*](http://Bump.sh)* API, Twitter API v2, Accounts \(References\)*.

**Save Details & Sync Button**

- Click **Save Details & Sync** to finalize synchronization.
- Docuwiz pushes the selected files to your configured repository branch.

## **Prerequisites for Generating a Personal Access Token**

Before connecting Docuwiz to GitHub or GitLab, ensure the following prerequisites are met:

- You must have an active **GitHub** or **GitLab** account.
- A repository must be created in your account.
- The repository must contain your Swagger specification files \(**.yaml**, **.json**, or **.md**\).

### **Generating a Personal Access Token**

***Github:***

![](data:image/png;base64,)

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Figure 3: Generating token in github

Follow these steps to create a fine grained personal access token in GitHub:

1. In the upper\-right corner of GitHub, click your **profile picture**, then click **Settings**.
1. In the left sidebar, scroll down and select **Developer settings**.
1. Select **Fine\-grained tokens**.
1. Configure the token:
  - **Token name**
  - **Expiration** \(GitHub requires an expiry date\)
  - **Resource owner** \(your account or an organization\)
  - **Repositories**  Select specific repositories or all \(ensure the repo with Swagger specs is included\)
1. Configure **Permissions** \(minimum required for pull/push operations\). **Repository permissions**:
  - *Actions*  Read and write
  - *Metadata*  Read
1. Select **Generate token** to create the token, or click **Cancel** to discard the operation \(see Figure 3\).

***Gitlab:***

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Figure 4: Generating token in gitlab

Follow these steps to create a personal access token in GitLab:

1. On the left sidebar, select your **avatar**.
1. Select **Edit Profile**.
1. In the left sidebar, select **Access Tokens**.
1. Select **Add new token**.
1. Enter a **Token name**.
1. \(Optional\) Enter a **description** for the token.
1. Specify an **Expiration date**.
  - The token expires at 00:00:00 UTC on the selected date.
  - If no date is specified, GitLab assigns a default expiry of 365 days.
  - GitLab 17.6\+ allows extending the expiry limit to 400 days.
1. Select the **required scopes**, such as api, read\_api, read\_user, read\_repository, write\_repository, and any additional scopes your workflow requires.
1. Select **Create** **personal access token** to create the token, or click **Cancel** to discard the operation \(see Figure 4\).
